{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489561"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:21:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"691"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/691"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.08,0.09,0.26,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115907"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/691"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97903"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1765"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7292"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49540"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115907"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shown (Image) is part of a standard procedure called an intra-operative choledochogram (cholangiogram). This procedure is performed during a cholecystectomy to examine the anatomy of the biliary tree and identify any potential pathological issues, such as a stone in the common bile duct. The cystic duct is cannulated and contrast injected to outline the biliary system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"From the image shown above, what is the anatomical defect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal anatomy","Choledochal cyst","Stone in the common bile duct","Anomalous cyst duct","Narrowing of the sphincter of Oddi"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case the cystic duct can be seen to join the right posterior hepatic duct. In normal anatomy, the common hepatic duct is joined by the cyst duct to form the common bile duct (Image 2). In the overlay to this image:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA = cystic duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EB = right hepatic duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC = left hepatic duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ED = common hepatic duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EE = common bile duct\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn\u003Cstrong\u003E anomalous cystic duct\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital abnormality characterised by an unusual position, shape, or size of the cystic duct, which connects the gallbladder to the common bile duct. It can be associated with other malformations of the gallbladder and can be identified through an intra-operative cholangiogram during a cholecystectomy. Individuals with an anomalous cystic duct may have an increased risk of gallstone formation and may require additional treatment or surgery to correct. Recognising the typical biliary anatomy and understanding the principles of X-ray imaging can aid in the diagnosis of this condition. This anomaly is a rare occurrence, present in less than 1% of the population, and it may present along with other congenital abnormalities such as anomalous pancreaticobiliary duct junction or choledochal cysts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrom the surgical perspective, the most important aspect of recognising this anatomical anomaly is to avoid ligating and damaging the right posterior hepatic duct, which could easily be mistaken for the cystic duct. Althought the specifics are beyond the scope of a medical student, being able to identify normal and abnormal anatomy is important. For those interested there is the Blumgart Classification of biliary tree anomolies. In addition, the cystic duct can have various courses; being short, long, attaching laterally or medially to the common hepatic duct to form the common bile duct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echoledochal cyst \u003C/strong\u003Eis a congenital dilation or enlargement of the common bile duct (CBD). It is a rare condition that occurs due to a structural abnormality in the bile duct system. It can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, jaundice, and recurrent infections. It may also increase the risk of developing cancer of the bile ducts. Treatment for choledochal cysts typically involves surgical removal. When evaluating a choledochal cyst, a cholangiogram is a common imaging procedure used to visualise the bile ducts. On a cholangiogram, a choledochal cyst appears as a well-defined cystic structure in the region of the CBD. The cyst is usually seen as a localised dilatation or enlargement of the bile duct, often resembling a sac or pouch. The extent and shape of the cyst may vary depending on the specific type of choledochal cyst present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sphincter of Oddi is a complex of four smooth muscle sphincters within the duodenal wall. It surrounds, and helps fix to the duodenum, the duct of Wirsung (the main pancreatic duct), common bile duct and the ampulla of Vater. \u003Cstrong\u003ENarrowing of the sphincter of Oddi \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be seen on cholangiogram as a focal or diffuse constriction in the area of the sphincter of Oddi. Additionally, the narrowing may be accompanied by other cholangiogram findings, such as dilatation or widening of the bile ducts upstream from the sphincter, none of which can be seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA stone in the bile duct\u003C/strong\u003E may appear as a radiopaque or radio dense object on cholangiogram, but there is no such evidence on the cholangiogram featured in this question.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal anatomy \u003C/strong\u003Eof cystic duct can be observed in the cholangiogram (via ERCP) below (Image 1).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anomalous cystic duct anatomy occurs in less than 1% of the population and can be identified on intraoperative cholangiography.","Recognition of biliary anatomical variants is crucial during cholecystectomy to prevent inadvertent injury to hepatic ducts."],"references":["https://www.grepmed.com/images/11546/cholangiogram-biliary-anatomy. (Image)","Yamamoto-Moreno J, Gomez-Fernandez R, Iturbide-Aguirre A, et al. Bile duct injury in an anatomical varian of the posterior right hepatic duct draining in the cystic duct: case report. International Journal of Reaseach in Medical Sciences. 2022;10(8). Available at: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/362277362_Bile_duct_injury_in_an_anatomical_variant_of_the_posterior_right_hepatic_duct_draining_in_the_cystic_duct_case_report"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97903"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"691"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20033"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20034"},{"type":"media","id":"20035"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20033"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/49a3cce5-fd53-44e0-bd8c-b5a8bb1d0faa.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/49a3cce5-fd53-44e0-bd8c-b5a8bb1d0faa.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":396,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"20034","links"